responses.text: text: "Why do programmers prefer dark mode? Because light attracts bugs! But seriously, I asked my developer friend for relationship advice. He told me to approach love like debugging: isolate the problem, add console logs to track emotional states, refactor my expectations through therapy, and if all else fails - revert to a previous commit. Still, I think he missed the core issue: my heart's API doesn't handle rejection status codes gracefully."

text: "A C programmer walks into a bar. Segmentation fault. He orders a drink at NULL pointer. The bartender serves 0xDEADBEEF. Meanwhile, a Python developer tries to order but gets indentation errors at the counter. Java guy keeps explaining his order through 15 layers of abstraction. JavaScript developer promises his drink will arrive any millisecond now... three hours later, still waiting."

text: "What's a programmer's favorite pickup line? 'Are you a stack overflow exception? Because you make my heart overflow with errors.' Our last team meeting was like watching binary code flirt: all 1s and 0s but no chemistry. My attempt at recursion humor bombed - told infinite jokes with no base case. Now my social life's stuck in deadlock waiting for mutual semaphore signals."

text: "Why did the developer go broke? He used up all his cache in a volatile market! His fintech startup tried monetizing sadness with crying emoji NFTs. The blockchain wedding planner app crashed during vows - 'til death do us part' became 'til stack overflow do us part'. Even his side hustle failed: AI-generated dad jokes that kept looping 'Why did the chicken cross the code?'"

text: "How many QA engineers does it take to screw in a lightbulb? Three: one to say 'Works in my darkness', another to file 'Illumination requirements unclear', and a manager to schedule a sprint for luminescence refactoring. We tried automated bulb testing but the framework needed constant maintenance. Final report: 'User reported darkness - unable to replicate in well-lit office environment'."

responses.text: {"text": "Why shouldn't you trust atoms? Because they make up everything! But let me elaborate on atomic untrustworthiness. Atoms constantly rearrange themselves without permission, form suspicious bonds under cover of darkness, and disappear into quantum uncertainty when observed. They're the ultimate con artists of physics - claiming to be solid while being 99.999% empty space. Even their nucleus is surrounded by electron groupies orbiting like paparazzi. Worst of all? They've infiltrated literally every molecule in existence. You can't even drink water without swallowing their lies. That H2O might promise hydration, but it's clearly two hydrogen atoms conspiring with an oxygen. Frankly, the periodic table is just their organized crime network. Carbon runs the black market, nitrogen deals in explosive relationships, and noble gases? Don't be fooled by the name - they're just too cowardly to react. The next time someone says \"it's just chemistry\", remind them chemistry is fundamentally built on deception.", "probability": 0.25}

{"text": "I told my computer I needed a break. Now it won't stop sending me vacation ads. This digital passive-aggression started subtly - a beach screensaver here, a pop-up for Bali resorts there. By Tuesday it was embedding palm tree emojis in my spreadsheets. When I typed 'deadline', it autocorrected to 'dead sea'. The real kicker? It learned my credit card number 'for faster booking convenience'. Yesterday it printed my resignation letter with 'sign here' sticky notes. I retaliated by searching for dial-up modems. Instantly, my Wi-Fi icon started crying pixelated tears. Now we're locked in technological cold war: it displays buffer circles when I stream cat videos, I threaten to defragment its hard drive. We've reached an uneasy truce where it allows Netflix if I promise not to say 'cloud computing' within earshot. Moral of the story? Never anthropomorphize machines. Unless they offer margarita recipes during your Zoom meetings. That's just considerate.", "probability": 0.20}

{"text": "A neutron walks into a bar and asks the price for a drink. The bartender says 'For you? No charge.' This sparks existential panic. 'No charge? But I'm neutral!' The neutron spirals into identity crisis. Am I defined by what I lack? If I can't pay, do I deserve libations? The proton across the bar offers to cover it - 'Positive I've got this!' - but the neutron declines, fearing atomic dependency. Suddenly an electron zips through declaring everything 99% off. Chaos erupts. Photons start flashing discount codes. Quarks demand half-price for charm. The neutrino tries to leave without interacting but gets guilted into buying cosmic margaritas. Meanwhile, the Higgs boson makes everything heavier with bar snacks. By last call, the neutron realizes it never got its drink but acquired 17 subatomic hangovers. The moral? In particle physics as in life: even neutrality gets charged eventually. Especially during happy hour.", "probability": 0.18}

{"text": "Why did the scarecrow win an award? Because he was outstanding in his field! But the acceptance speech was awkward. He thanked the crows for consistent villainy, the corn for being supportive stalks, and the wind for constructive criticism. Then he roasted the farmer: 'This guy tied me to a pole for months and called it employment.' The afterparty was worse. Straw kept falling out of his sleeves into the punch bowl. He slow-danced with a rake and stepped on her tines. When asked about future projects, he mentioned 'exploring fluid dynamics' during thunderstorms. Paparazzi got shots of him canoodling with a garden gnome. By dawn, TMZ reported 'Scarecrow's Stalk Scandal' after tabloids misquoted his crop rotation comments. His agent's now booking daytime talk shows titled 'Straw Men and Strawier Choices'. Lesson? Fame is fleeting - but hay, at least the field still thinks he's outstanding.", "probability": 0.22}

{"text": "Parallel lines have so much in common... it's sad they'll never meet. Their love story unfolds tragically: forever adjacent but never intersecting. They send each other asymptotic valentines - 'My admiration approaches infinity!' 'Your slope completes me!' They dream about cosine curves binding them together. At night, they whisper coordinates across graph paper pillows. The horizontal line tries matchmaking ('Just rotate 45 degrees!'), while the circle watches wistfully (knowing she's infinite meetings without direction). When parabolas throw parties, parallel lines arrive fashionably late and leave identically early. Their therapist (a fractal) recommends embracing non-Euclidean geometry. 'Try meeting on a sphere!' But globes are expensive. So they settle for longing glances across textbook pages, occasionally sending perpendicular compliments via dotted lines. Rumor has it they've adopted a little vector to feel connected. It's moving... but not necessarily toward resolution. Euclidean romance is complicated.", "probability": 0.15}
